<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[192,1440,669,758]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,335,669,693]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bechyne" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[343,550,669,693]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weyrauchi">
<emphasis box="[343,550,669,693]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Beltia weyrauchi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[780,941,669,693]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tisingalita">
<emphasis box="[780,941,669,693]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">B. tisingalita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that both species have acute teeth on the profemora. In 
<taxonomicName box="[418,579,702,726]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tisingalita">
<emphasis box="[418,579,702,726]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">B. tisingalita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the pronotum is more strongly convergent anteriorly and the body is more elongate than in 
<emphasis box="[469,636,734,758]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bechyne" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[469,632,734,758]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weyrauchi">B. weyrauchi</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="29.[192,1440,782,1066]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,323,783,807]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Remarks.</emphasis>
Bechynĕ described both forms in a key to Peruvian 
<taxonomicName box="[955,1100,782,806]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Colaspoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[955,1100,782,806]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Colaspoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, giving leg color as a distinguishing character: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bechyne" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[433,591,815,839]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weyrauchi">
<emphasis box="[433,591,815,839]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">C. weyrauchi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described as having testaceous legs, whereas the legs are metallic in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bechyne" authorityYear="1950" box="[224,472,847,871]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Colaspoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chanchamayensis">
<emphasis box="[224,472,847,871]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">C. chanchamayensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the three specimens studied here, the legs are yellowish brown in the male, dark reddish brown with metallic bluish green femora in one female, and dark metallic bluish green in a second female. As already seen in several species, leg color by itself is not a useful character for delineating species in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1881" box="[359,432,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[359,432,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Beltia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Since 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bechyne" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[518,676,944,968]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weyrauchi">
<emphasis box="[518,676,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">C. weyrauchi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has page priority in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bechyne, J." box="[924,1142,944,969]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" pagination="205 - 236" refId="ref24946" refString="Bechyne, J. 1950 b. Eumolpides americains nouveaux ou peu connus. Entomologische Arbeiten aus dem Museum G. Frey 1: 205 - 236." type="journal article" year="1950">Bechynĕ’s (1950b)</bibRefCitation>
publication, I chose that name for the new combination. Bechynĕ’s description of the locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bechyne" authorityYear="1950" box="[1059,1308,977,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Colaspoides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chanchamayensis">
<emphasis box="[1059,1308,977,1001]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">C. chanchamayensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes a note: “type, Mus. Javier Prado á 
<collectingRegion box="[587,654,1009,1033]" country="Peru" name="Lima" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Lima</collectingRegion>
”, which appears to be contradicted by the labeled 
<typeStatus box="[1259,1363,1009,1033]" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">holotype</typeStatus>
in the USNM. This species is known only from a small area in the eastern Peruvian Andes (
<figureCitation box="[1237,1325,1042,1066]" captionStart="Figures 78–79" captionStartId="43.[191,286,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[192,1441,412,1699]" captionTargetId="figure@43.[189,1443,412,1702]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Figures 78–79. Distribution maps for Beltia spp. 78) Northwestern South America: B. confusa (star), B. gorgona (inverted triangles), B. placidula (blue circles), B. rugosa (red circle), B. weyrauchi (square). 79) Ecuador: B. awapita (hexagon), B. ledesmae (squares), B. napoensis (triangles), B. talaga (circle), B. tsachila (star)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713527" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713527/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="28">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
